	annote = {Notes
The authors present a computational sketch for how decisions are made. They take an example of a driver deciding to steer left (L) or right (R) in order to avoid collision with a sudden obstacle.
The driver might consider his current direction (a) of momentum in order to decide. (If he is already moving to the right, it might be easier to steer right). To compute this direction the driver can take into account two streams of sensory evidence: the visual data (I) and the vestibular data (V).
Choice and certainty
Thus, the driver makes a probabilistic inference about which action to take:

P(d{\textbar}I,V)
I would also add a goal here: P(d{\textbar}I,V,g)

where d {\textbackslash}in \{L, R\}. Since this inference is probabilistic it possesses an uncertainty property. This is a posterior over all available choices. The spread of this distribution can be regarded as choice uncertainty (e.g., action uncertainty) which we can also call conflict. Detecting this state increases arousal and inhibition and signals the need for control and the need to attend to sensory (bottom up data).
Achievement and confidence
The driver can also make another probabilistic inference about whether a particular decision is correct:

P(success{\textbar}d,I,V)

Where success {\textbackslash}in \{1, 0\}. This is a distinct probability distribution that is always binary according to the authors. While action uncertainty may be continuous (for continuous actions), achievement uncertainty is always binary.

I guess the weight-update mechanism corresponds to action uncertainty reduction. As the underlying task module gets better, the uncertainty about which decision to make, P(d{\textbar}I,V) decreases. 

Certainty vs confidence
The authors propose that certainty and confidence should be differentiated. Certainty/uncertainty refers to what Meyniel et al. (2015) called distributional uncertainty (more or less). It is the uncertainty of the P(d{\textbar}I,V) posterior -- what decision to make, given the data and prior knowledge. Confidence, on the other hand refers to the degree of belief in the truthfulness of a proposition. The proposition can be anything from "Nigeria is the most populous African country" to "I will score a goal in the next match".
Why confidence?
The authors consider a legitimate question: if a posterior like P(d{\textbar}I,V) can be represented, why do we need to represent limited-summary like confidence?
The authors propose that sometimes, confidence is all that is needed for a task. In other cases, the authors argue that confidence is a way to approximate the posterior P(d{\textbar}I,V)
Distributional certainty can be used to make decisions. That is, if a particular context-input X is perceived, the agent can make judgments about the latent state Y of the environment, e.g., P(Y{\textbar}X).  Y can be discrete (e.g., driver heading to the right vs left) or continuous (e.g., driver is heading y degrees relative to reference point). The probability of Y states is only conditioned on X, so variance of P(Y{\textbar}X) reflects certainty as opposed to confidence. To represent confidence, the agent needs to entertain a particular value (or a range of values) of Y, e.g. P(Y=y{\textbar}X). This conditioning on a choice, as the authors call it, is what distinguishes confidence from certainty.  
 },
